     <h4>
      Your Comments
     </h4>
     <p>
      <br />
      <em>
       Stop hiding behind the pristine dune excuse to stop the community oceanway from Bilinga to Tugun.
       <br />
       <br />
       The dunes along the planned Bilinga to Tugun Oceanway are called 'urbanised dunes'.  They are not pristine dunes as some would have you believe.
       <br />
       <br />
       At present there is concrete paths, slabs of concrete, concrete steps and paved areas, this has all been done by residents and developers on this dune area.
       <br />
       <br />
       An existing beachfront house had a relaxation approved to add a new covered deck pushing it very close to the dune area.
       <br />
       <br />
       Some of the dunes at the Tugun end have been completely flattened and turfed, all the dune grasses have been removed.
       <br />
       <br />
       Trees have been killed and cut down to improve views.  If you walk or ride on the present oceanway path from Bilinga you will see how green those dunes are.
       <br />
       <br />
       Photos were taken by a Dune Care representative of a resident in the dunes mowing the dune grass.  This has all been uncovered since the partial removal of illegal encroachments and the community has been able to access this area.
       <br />
       <br />
       If these dune protectors cared so much, they would be asking for the concrete and the remaining illegal encroachments to be removed.
       <br />
       <br />
       They would also be asking Gold Coast council to explain why a house extension was allowed to come so close to the dunes they want protected.
       <br />
       <br />
       The Bilinga to Tugun oceanway is to promote inclusion within our community for all.  Not completing it only promotes exclusion.
      </em>
      <br />
      <strong>
       A. Dennis, Bilinga. GC Sun 9 July 2015.
      </strong>
     </p>
     <p>
      <em>
       If the current discussion about beachside thoroughfares in Currumbin, Tugun and Bilinga is about public access, Cr Chris Robbins, then your claim in the Sun (25 Jun)
       <a href="http://www.goldcoastbulletin.com.au/news/gold-coast/petition-push-for-bilinga-to-tugun-oceanway-as-debate-rages/story-fnj94idh-1227434903437">
        <strong>
         read article here,
        </strong>
       </a>
       that the public access stretch between Tomewin Street Currumbin and Flat Rock was now "very firm and suitable for wheelchairs, bikes and prams" is not quite right.
       <br />
       <br />
       I can see why you would take the view as, sitting in a car looking down the stretch from Tomewin St, the first 30m of the track is firm and easily navigable.  But then it drops away beyond sight and one has to actually walk the track to the footbridge at Flat Rock Creek to see its true condition.  Aside from the three sand 'bunkers' stretching across the neck of Len Wort Park near Flat Rock Creek which are annoyances for all, you could claim that it is navigable for sure-footed walkers, those on bikes, and not too much of a problem for those pushing prams.
       <br />
       <br />
       But the rutted areas, erosion, slope and holes along the track make it totally unsuitable for wheelchairs, or those relying on 'wheelie walkers'.
       <br />
       <br />
       And since you raised it, a sealed path would overcome such obstacles plus complete the beachside path connection between Kropp Park Tugun and Pacific Parade Currumbin.  It would also allow for easier and safer use after sunset.
       <br />
       <br />
       However, on this I note your general claim that it has been left as a 'green corridor' because of opposition to a sealed path.
       <br />
       <br />
       Has there been community consultation undertaken around this or simply representation from one or two land owners there who do not want a path?
       <br />
       <br />
       And if so, is it just me or does this sound familiar to some of the discussion around the Tugun to Bilinga Oceanway?
       <br />
       <br />
       So if accessibility is the primary issue, I invite Cr Robbins to revist both tracks - the current dirt track along the Tugun to Bilinga beachfront and the Flat Rock to Tomewin St Currumbin track - for an accessibility update.
      </em>
      <br />
      <strong>
       K Horne, Tugun.  GC Sun 9 July 2015.
      </strong>
     </p>
     <p>
      <br />
      <em>
       Gold Coast City Councillor Chris Robbins' intention to provide us with a thin white painted line along Golden Four Drive at Bilinga to presumably protect us from tons of steel hurtling towards us at speed is of a bygone era.
       <br />
       <br />
       And apart from lack of safety it is dull and noisy.  Let her show us her 'metal' by providing us with a safe passage, and a scenic one at that.  The land seaward of the properties is not private land, it is our land - it is our unformed Pacific Parade.  Let it be used for its intended purpose.  A grassed path is now well established; benefit yourself with a quiet, clean ocean walk.
      </em>
      <br />
      <strong>
       Ian Pratt, Bilinga.  GC Sun 9 July 2015,
      </strong>
     </p>
