     <p>
      <br />
      <em>
       Gold Coast City Councillor Chris Robbins has told us that noisy and dangerous Golden Four Drive is her preferred option for us - her constituents - to ride and walk between Tugun and Bilinga rather than upon the scenic and safe unformed road reserve seaward of the properties along Golden Four Drive.
       <br />
       This, she says, is because that was the result of her second consultation.  Cr Robbins adds that her second consultation only gave us the choice of Golden Four Drive because that was the outcome of her first consultation.
       <br />
       Hence, if her first consultation was flawed then so are the findings of her second.  Her first was flawed.
       <br />
       First, no one had the opportunity of walking the road reserve seaward of the properties in Golden Four Drive, for these owners had fenced us out.
       <br />
       Second, Cr Robbins targeted that group of residents by sending each a letter inviting them to vote.
       <br />
       Third, residents were not told that if they voted for Golden Four Drive, they would lose their parking.  When the process of consulting targets a select group, the consultation is a farce.
       <br />
       Despite this, 34 per cent of that target group wanted the bike/walkway seaward of their properties, and 69 per cent of those who did not live on Golden Four Drive wanted to walk and ride seaward of those properties.
      </em>
      <br />
      <strong>
       Ian Pratt, Bilinga.  GC Sun, 4 June 2015.
      </strong>
     </p>
     <p>
      <em>
       I had Mother's Day breakfast at North Kirra Surf Club with my family - the food was excellent and I was delighted to see the number of families out walking along the beautiful beach path.
       <br />
       <br />
       I live in Currumbin and have joy in watching others walking and participating daily on the path from Currumbin to Tugun.
       <br />
       <br />
       What a pity the great work started by earlier Gold Coast City Council representatives has not continued especially when Queensland Government funds were allocated.
      </em>
      <br />
      <strong>
       Beverly Goss, Currumbin.  GC Sun, 11 June 2015
      </strong>
     </p>
     <p>
      <br />
      <em>
       It has been great to read the many letters protesting the off-hand attitude of the Gold Coast City towards the residents of the Southern Gold Coast.
       <br />
       <br />
       The Tugun to Bilinga Oceanway was designed and funded by the Gold Coast council and the Queensland Government, and was considered a vital piece of infrastructure, a scenic walkway connecting Bilinga to Tugun.
       <br />
       <br />
       Following a deeply flawed survey involving principally oceanfront residents reluctant to share the beach front road reserve, the construction was halted and the funding returned to the Queensland Government.
       <br />
       <br />
       We will continue the struggle to right this injustice levelled at Southern Gold Coasters who want no more than the other residents of the Gold Coast who enjoy the Oceanway at our many other beautiful beachfront suburbs.
      </em>
      <br />
      <strong>
       Barry Robinson, Friends of Currumbin.  GC Sun, 4 Jun 2015.
      </strong>
     </p>
     <p>
      <br />
      <em>
       At present the dunal area from Tooloona St TUGUN to the Bilinga Surf Club is
selfishly controlled by a number of residents [not all] that live along this
particular area and for some reason consider that they, and no one else
should have access to the area.
       <br />
       Unfortunately our misinformed local Councillor also appears to exhibit a
denial attitude against the local area residents as well as a great number
of Gold Coasters and visitors from Australia and overseas that the Oceanway
is not wanted .How much further from the truth can this be and what is
required to get the majority of peoples wishes through to Council that the
Oceanway is not a bucket list wish but a very important project that is
required for the present and future residents of this area.
       <br />
       The most recent Resident information night at Tugun Bowls club to advise
locals of the proposed upgrade of Golden Four Drive to include wider bicycle
lanes, changes to vehicle parking and traffic was met with great opposition
and requests were made to bring the Oceanway access back to fruition.
Unfortunately our Councillor, once again refused to take notice or enter
into any discussion as the information night was to deal with Golden Four
Drive and no other issues.
       <br />
       The bicycle lane alteration to Golden Four Drive is only relevant to the
riders of racing type bicycles who are looking for a better and wider lane
to utilize and whilst this is commendable it does not in anyway, shape or
form give the majority of people any benefit what so ever. The current media
hysteria re the so called bad attitude culture between cyclists and
motorists only adds to the unbalanced reaction from the Council and road
authorities. The recent comments from the Council and Councillor that the
cost of the proposed Golden Four Drive upgrade would blow out because some
one forgot about the under ground Gas line that, incidentally was up graded
only a few years back is also beyond belief and makes the initial selection
of this direction of expenditure completely farcical.
       <br />
       Back to the dunal area discussion,

the few people that are against the Oceanway are the very people who have
desecrated the area by bringing in exotic plants, making lawned areas of the
dunes, building unapproved structures, parking boats and trailers on the
dunes and after fencing this public area off have the audacity to hinder and
deny fellow residents use of the area as it may effect their privacy!!
Heaven help us when we have this mentality of people as neighbours and in
public office.
       <br />
       The State Government has declared the area as public space and the Gold
Coast City Council as the nominees to monitor this space and yet the Council
still makes mockery of the debate by the results of questionable local
surveys and consultations that they use as an argument.
       <br />
       All open meetings with residents, local and others as well as well informed
inputs from knowledgeable persons all agree the Oceanway can only be a major
benefit to the area and the use of this structure can be used by all
including walkers, casual bike riders,the elderly and the  incapacitated,
Mums and Dads and their children whether in prams or on bikes with training
wheels, and all those who just stroll and take in the delightful scenery and
atmosphere. Perhaps some of the opponents may also enjoy the area ever so
much more.
       <br />
       Lets stop this dilly dallying and move on !!!!!!!
      </em>
      <br />
      <strong>
       Terry &amp; Jeanette C.
      </strong>
     </p>
     <p>
      <br />
      <em>
       My name is Mark Wotherspoon - I don't have the option of walking, running or riding for exercise.  I have to use a wheelchair.
       <br />
       I regularly use and enjoy the existing Oceanway between Snapper Rocks and Bilinga Surf Clubs.
       <br />
       When I reach Bilinga Surf Club, I come to the end of the pathway.  I have to stop there because the 1.7km of public road reserve along the foreshore, Bilinga to Tugun, is not suitable for wheelchair travel.
       <br />
       Only walkers, runners and mountain bikes can use this public road reserve.
       <br />
       The footpath on Golden Four Drive is a disgrace and impossible to use in a wheelchair (I have tried).  I would not even attempt to use Golden Four Drive as in my experienced opinion it is far too dangerous.
       <br />
       Our Gold Coast Councillor, Chris Robbins, seems to think that disabled people should be able to use Golden Four Drive, now and in the future, where we must be viligant for cars exiting from the 65 driveways, negotiate impossible road crossing ramps and breathe in the pollution from cars, trucks and buses of the Gold Coast Highway.
       <br />
       In October 2012, council resolved to remove illegal encroachments from the Tugun to Bilinga public road reserve.  It is, I understand, their legal responsibility to maintain public road reserves to an acceptable standard for all users.
       <br />
       Clearly council has not provided equitable access here and I quote from the Engineering Services Committee meeting on October 11, 2012, adopted at council meeting October 23, 2012 - "Item 9.  Risk management number 8 ... Access along the 1.7km of beachfront public road reserve does not currently meet the requirements of the Disability Discrimination Act 1992.  Whilst the removal of type A and B encroachments will improve accessibility for many people, the road reserve will still not provide disability compliant access in accordance with the DDA."
       <br />
       Why am I and other disabled persons treated like second-class citizens?
       <br />
       Why are others able to enjoy walking along the foreshore?
       <br />
       Where is the truth on council website that states that the Oceanway is a disability project?
       <br />
       And where is the truth on this website where the council states that they have an Accessible and Inclusive Action Plan 2014 - 2019?
       <br />
       I call on the chief executive of GCCC to take immediate action to rectify this totally unacceptable and discriminatory situation by committing to complete the Tugun to Bilinga section of the Oceanway - NOW!
      </em>
      <br />
      <strong>
       Mark Wotherspoon, Currumbin Waters.  Letter to Editor, GC Sun, 28 May 2015.
      </strong>
     </p>
     <p>
      <img alt="Mark Wotherspoon" src="Images/box/spoon.JPG" />
     </p>
