     <p>
      <em>
       Renton Winders in the Sun (23/5), you are simply wrong and your arguments don't stack up.  Gold Coast City Council Engineering report on the concept states that the build of the Bilinga-Tugun Oceanway section is feasible and not problematic as you claim.
       <br />
       As to cost, the 2011 report says it would cost less than $4m, $2.5m to build the path and $1.5m in contingencies, design and managing the build.  The only reason it is not happening is because Councillor Chris Robbins has repeatedly blocked the building of the path, specially introducing motions in council meetings to successfully stymie it.
       <br />
       So unless Cr Robbins is voted out next year, the path will never be built.
       <br />
       This path is not just for locals but for all the Coast residents and for tourists from far and near.  It would be great for residents and small business in the area.
       <br />
       As for dune care, the dozen "private" paths running from the back of properties to the beach through the dunes clearly speak of selfishness and not of "care for the environment" and so do the private structures built on public land that remain in various states of disrepair.
       <br />
       Your nimby enviro warrior act is hollow.  Most people are not upset with the residents involved wanting to protect their privileged position, they get it.  The way that they try to maintain this privilege is what gets up most people's craw.  This path needs to be built along the foreshore where it belongs.  The more this is resisted, the more fractured our community will become.
      </em>
      <br />
      <strong>
       Gerrit Van Duk, Tugun.  GC Sun 7 May 2015.
